Ia to fibrinogen","von Willebrand factor bridges collagen to platelet glycoprotein Ib","Platelet glycoprotein VI binding directly to collagen","Platelet P-selectin binding to endothelial cells","Thrombin activation of platelet protease receptors"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003Evon Willebrand factor bridges collagen to platelet glycoprotein Ib\u003C/strong\u003E receptors in the initial phase of platelet adhesion. This interaction is crucial as it allows platelets to adhere to the vessel wall even under high shear conditions found in arterioles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect binding of platelet glycoprotein IIb/IIIa to fibrinogen\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during platelet aggregation, after initial adhesion and activation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelet glycoprotein VI binding directly to collagen\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after initial tethering and contributes to platelet activation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelet P-selectin binding to endothelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during inflammation, not primary haemostasis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombin activation of platelet protease receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in platelet activation, not initial adhesion\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter the initial von Willebrand factor-mediated adhesion, other receptors engage with the subendothelial matrix to strengthen platelet attachment and trigger activation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["von Willebrand factor acts as a bridge between exposed collagen and platelet glycoprotein Ib receptors during initial platelet adhesion.","Platelet adhesion is the first step in primary haemostasis, occurring before platelet activation and aggregation."],"references":["Asbury, C., Rieke, F.